# read in the data using a relative path that starts from the analysis file directory
d <- read_csv("../../../data/3_final_merged_data/first_shifts/speed_acc_adult_ng_fstshift_tidy.csv")

Check the data

The goal of this section is to make sure the data match our expectations, or in other words, we are testing our data. Usually this involves comparing a known value to the number actually in the data set. For example, I know how I ran 20 participants, do I have 20 unique participant IDs?

This chapter from the book R for Data Science is a good reference for writing code to manipulate data to do data sanity checks.

Explore data via visualization

This is a great book chapter on data visualization using the ggplot2 R package

Visualize data distributions

My goal when I visualize the distribution of a variable is usually to check if there any data points that look like outliers (really different from the other values in the sample). There are more precise, quantitative ways to define outlier, but the visualization helps us spot them quickly. If some observations look really different, I then try to reason about why that might be the case: data entry error? equipment measurement error?

What about Reaction Times (RT)?

KM note: Nice job! Small point, but theres no need to load the library in each chunk. Just need to do it once, which we usually do at the beginning of the document. Also, theres no need to wrap the d object in the data.frame() function since it is already a data frame.

#data.frame(d)
ggplot(d) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = subid, y = rt))

geom_histogram() is a good one for viewing the overall distribution of RTs in the experiment.

ggplot(d, aes(x = rt)) +
  geom_histogram()

What about Accuracy?

ggplot(d) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = subid, fill = shift_accuracy)) +

KM note: This is a great exploratory plot! We can see that a couple of participants are doing weird things that we would want to investigate further. The only thing I changed was the angle of the x-axis text, so we can see the subids more easily.

filter the data

Lets filter out the participants who was not a native speaker of English

d.filt <- d %>% filter(!(subid %in% c("speed_acc_adult_ng_1")))

Next, lets remove extreme RTs.

d.filt %<>% filter(rt <= 1.5)

KM code after here

Lets visualize accuracy collapsing across the gaze and noise conditions. First we are going to summarise to get a proportion correct for each participant and condition. Then we aggregate again to get an overall proportion correct for each condition.

# aggregate accuracy at the participant level
ss <- d.filt %>% 
  filter(!is.na(shift_accuracy),
         shift_type %in% c("C_T", "C_D")) %>% 
  group_by(condition_long, subid, shift_accuracy) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  group_by(subid, condition_long) %>% 
  mutate(total_trials = sum(n),
         prop = round(n / total_trials, 2)) 

# aggregate at the condition level
ms <- ss %>% 
  filter(shift_accuracy == "correct") %>% 
  group_by(condition_long) %>% 
  multi_boot_standard(column = "prop")

Now make a boxplot of the accuracy data for each condition. Note that we have to first filter out the proprotion incorrect rows, so we are only seeing the proprotion correct data.

ss %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = condition_long, y = prop)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Plot the mean accuracy and confidence interval for each condition.

ms %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = condition_long, y = mean)) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin = summary_ci_lower, ymax = summary_ci_upper)) +
  ylim(0.4, 1.1) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5, linetype = "dashed")

Interpretation here: How would you interpret this plot in a sentence or two? It appears that people are more accurate in the no gaze conditions (regardless of of noise vs no noise) compared to the gaze conditions. ### Visualize Reaction Time

What is the overall RT for adults in the experiment?

d %>% 
  filter(!is.na(shift_accuracy),
          shift_type %in% c("C_T", "C_D")) %>% 
  group_by(subid, condition_long) %>% 
  summarise(m_rt = mean(rt)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = condition_long, y = m_rt)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

What about RTs for correct vs.incorrect shifts?

rr <- d %>% 
  filter(!is.na(shift_accuracy)) %>% # remove trials where they did not shift
  group_by(condition_long, subid, shift_accuracy, rt) %>% 
  summarise(n = n()) %>% 
  group_by(subid, condition_long)

# aggreate at the condition level(correct)
rs <- rr %>% 
  filter(shift_accuracy == "correct") %>% 
  group_by(condition_long) %>% 
  summarise(mean_correct = mean(rt),
            sd_correct = sd(rt))

# aggreate at the condition level(incorrect)
rk <- rr %>% 
  filter(shift_accuracy == "incorrect") %>% 
  group_by(condition_long) %>% 
  summarise(mean_correct = mean(rt),
            sd_correct = sd(rt))

Boxplot

rr %>% 
  filter(shift_accuracy == "correct") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = condition_long, y = rt)) +
  geom_boxplot()

RT Distributions

acc_colors <- c("grey10", "black")
fill_vals <- c("grey90", "darkviolet")

p <- d.filt %>% 
  filter(is.na(rt) == F) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = forcats::fct_rev(condition_long), y = rt, color = shift_accuracy, 
             fill = shift_accuracy)) +
  ggbeeswarm::geom_quasirandom(shape = 21) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = acc_colors) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = fill_vals) +
  labs(y = "RT (sec)", x = NULL) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "right") + 
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(size = 16, 
                                    face = "bold"), 
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 16,
                                    face = "bold"), axis.text.x = element_text(size = 14),
        axis.text.y = element_text(size = 14)) +
  coord_flip()
